Subject: Re: Voodoo / StormMesa / CGFX
From: Hans-Joerg Frieden <Hans-JoergF@hyperion-software.de>
Date: Thu, 1 Feb 2001 16:56:30 +0100

Hi!

On Thursday 01 February 2001 10:38, Oliver Gantert wrote:
> I wonder if StormMesa supports those features not available on
> Permedia2 or Virge cards (e.g. mipmapping). Now that I have a
> Voodoo3 (but never seen it in action, as there's no CGFX4 driver
> available) I'd like to tune up my 3D engine, of course.

The Virge does support Mipmapping including trilinear filtern, although its 
slow.
If the Warp3D driver supports it, StormMesa will automatically use the 
feature.

> Currently the BVision is still running and I had to remove the
> Prelude1200 from the clockport to install the Mediator board :(
>
> Back to the topic... how complete is StormMesa regarding the
> features of a Voodoo3?

See above. Since the Voodoo 3 supports considerably more blending modes than 
the Permedia2, you will get these when the Warp3D driver for the Voodoo 3 is 
out...

> When will OpenGL (or Mesa) be part of the OS?

Good question.

> Why doesn't the Hyperion (hi guys!) MiniGL have any lighting
> functions?

Because Heretic II doesn't use them. Neither does Shogo. You could 
theoretically hook them in, and you're welcome to try. However, it gives a 
speed advantage if lighting is not enabled since I can combine GL_MODELVIEW 
and GL_PROJECTION to a single matrix and keep them this way if no matrix 
change occurs. 

For lightning to work, you would need additional functions (like glMaterial) 
and you would need to hook into the pipeline. This is (in a certain sense) 
already in in the form of automatic texture coordinate calculation (which is 
used in Heretic II's "Reflection" spell).

> Does anybody have information about CGFX4 drivers for the
> Voodoo3-3000? Does an alpha/beta driver exist? Does the CGFX3
> alpha driver work with CGFX4?

Yes, it exists, and works very well, at least on this here GREX prototype. It 
even has overlay support, meaning it can run MPEG videos fullscreen. But it 
doesn't run AFAIK on the Mediator.

> How is the Warp3D driver developed? Are you using P96 or CGFX?

CGFX, since it is done on the G-REX. The Mediator driver will require a bit 
more additional work due to the bank switching, but it isn't really much 
work, and a matter of hours (I hope :-). There is much more work to do yet on 
the driver itself, since there is a lot of functionality (and optimizations) 
still missing. 

Right now the driver does a few things which are bad for bank switching. For 
example, textures are uploaded to their appropriate address. However, there 
are a few shortcuts that can be taken, for example, the Voodoo 3 has a 
texture upload port that is located close to the register space. I expect the 
final driver to be completely without bankswitching if the Mediator is set to 
8 MB window size. (there will of course be one switch in the W3D_LockHardware 
call). 

Best regards,
