> I hope you dont mind users using the code in this manner, but I think it
> is great to have the example and source available.

Sure, if somebody wants to use it as a basis, go ahead. There are a lot of 
basic things still to do, of course. 
For one, it's just rendering every cell, it's not doing proper visibility and 
depth sorting. The original idea was to add visibility blocking to each of 
the four sides of a cell, and do a depth-first traversal through the grid, 
only advancing if there's no blocker, and starting at the player's cell. 

Of course, there's also no collision detection code (I've written some code 
that checks if a vector and a given polygon do intersect, if somebody is 
interested, I can post it here). 

Plus, and that's the most critical part, it's just rendering. To make it into 
a game engine, a transport layer and object system would be needed, and 
that's not trivial...

All in all, you'd be better of with QuakeForge ;)

